		<p>
			As <xref ref="intro-piecewise-function-pieces"/> shows, only one piece is active at a time, and the others are turned OFF. This means that we can think of <m>g(t)</m> as a sum of three pieces, each multiplied by an ON-OFF switch that triggers at the right times. Such switches come in the form of a simple piecewise function that is <m>1</m> on a given interval and <m>0</m> otherwise. That is, we can write:
		</p>

		<me>
			g(t) =
			{\DLBb \sin t} \cdot
			\us{\large\text{on-off switch}}{
			\boxed{
			\left\{
			\begin{array}{l}
				1,\ \ \DLBb t \lt 0\\
				0,\ \ \small\text{otherwise}
			\end{array}
			\right.}}\ \
			+\ \
			{\DLGa 2e^{-t}} \cdot
			\us{\large\text{off-on-off switch}}{
			\boxed{
			\left\{
			\begin{array}{l}
				1,\ \ \DLGa 0 \ge t \lt 2\\
				0,\ \ \small\text{otherwise}
			\end{array}
			\right.}}\ \
			+\ \
			{\DLO 1.5} \cdot
			\us{\large\text{off-on switch}}{
			\boxed{
			\left\{
			\begin{array}{l}
				1,\ \ \DLO t \ge 2\\
				0,\ \ \small\text{otherwise}.
			\end{array}
			\right.}}
		</me>

		<p>
			The piecewise functions representing these switches are called <em>unit step functions</em> and they are the key to writing piecewise functions in a clean, compact way. In this section, will take a deeper look into these special functions that unlock a path to applying Laplace transforms to piecewise functions.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<subsection label="unit-step-switch-mindset">
		<title> Thinking in Terms of Switches </title>

		<introduction>
			<p>
				At this point, you've met the unit step and its main variants — shifted, reversed, and windowed. Before we move on, it's worth pausing to think about what these step functions really mean and how to use them effectively.
			</p>
		</introduction>

		<reading-questions label="rq-switch-mindset">
			<title> 👀 Pre-Reading Questions </title>
			<p>
				<exercise> placeholder: “If multiplying by <m>u_3(t)</m> turns something ON at <m>t=3</m>, what combination of step functions could turn it ON at 3 and OFF at 7?” </exercise>
			</p>
		</reading-questions>

		<p>
			Every step function you've seen is really just a :  
			<ul marker="square">
				<li><m>u_c(t)</m> flips ON at <m>t=c</m>.</li>
				<li><m>1-u_c(t)</m> flips OFF at <m>t=c</m>.</li>
				<li><m>u_c(t)-u_d(t)</m> flips ON at <m>t=c</m> and OFF at <m>t=d</m>.</li>
			</ul>
		</p>

		<aside xml:id="switch-mindset-language">
			<title> Thinking in “ON” and “OFF” </title>
			<p>
				This ON/OFF language is powerful for intuition — but keep the math in mind:  
				<ul marker="circle">
					<li>ON means “the function is multiplied by <m>1</m>,” so it passes through unchanged.</li>
					<li>OFF means “the function is multiplied by <m>0</m>,” so it is silenced completely.</li>
				</ul>
			</p>
		</aside>

		<p>
			By combining these step functions, you can “program” exactly when each part of a function is active. 
			For example:
			<me>
				f(t) = 3t \big( u_2(t) - u_5(t) \big)
			</me>
			means “let 3t run between <m>t=2</m> and <m>t=5</m>, but nowhere else.”
		</p>

		<example xml:id="ex-switch-combining">
			<title> Combining Switches </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Write a formula that equals <m>5</m> before <m>t=1</m>, equals <m>t^2</m> from <m>t=1</m> to <m>t=3</m>, and is zero afterward — using step functions.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution> placeholder solution here </solution>
		</example>

		<reading-questions label="rq-switch-reflection">
			<title> 📝 Reflect on Switch Combinations </title>
			<p>
				<exercise> placeholder: “Which step function turns a function OFF forever starting at t=4?” </exercise>
			</p>
		</reading-questions>

		<p>
			Thinking in switches makes complex piecewise behavior easier to write and to “see.” Each piece of a function is simply a part of the graph that's switched ON or OFF at exactly the right times. 
			In the next section, we'll combine all these switches to write entire piecewise functions in a single, seamless formula.
		</p>
	</subsection>

	<subsection label="piecewise-definition">
		<title> What Makes a Function Piecewise? </title>
	</subsection>

	<subsection label="piecewise-rewriting">
		<title> Rewriting a Piecewise Function in Step Form </title>

		<example><title> Switching ON Sine at <m>t = \sfrac{\pi}{2}</m> </title>
			<p>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Rewrite the function
						<me>
							g(t) = \left\{
							\begin{array}{ll}
								\sin t, \amp t \ge \sfrac{\pi}{2} \\
								0, \amp \text{otherwise}
							\end{array}
							\right.
						</me>
						using a unit step function.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</p>

			<solution>
				<p>
					Since <m>\sin t</m> turns ON at <m>t = \sfrac{\pi}{2}</m>, we multiply it by <m>u_{\sfrac{\pi}{2}}(t)</m>:
					<me>
						g(t) = \sin t \cdot u_{\sfrac{\pi}{2}}(t)
					</me>
				</p>
				<p>
					Plugging in <m>u_{\sfrac{\pi}{2}}(t)</m>, confirms we arrived at the correct piecewise function: 
					<md>
						<mrow>
							g(t) =
							\sin t \cdot \ub{
							\left\{
								\begin{array}{ll}
									1,	\amp t \ge \sfrac{\pi}{2}\\
									0,	\amp \text{otherwise}
								\end{array} 
							\right.
							}_{\large u_{\sfrac{\pi}{2}}(t)}
							\quad \amp =
							\left\{
								\begin{array}{ll}
									\sin(t) \cdot 1,	\amp t \ge \sfrac{\pi}{2}\\
									\sin(t) \cdot 0,	\amp \text{otherwise}
								\end{array} 
							\right.
						</mrow>
						<mrow>
							\amp =
							\left\{
								\begin{array}{ll}
									\sin(t),	\amp t \ge \sfrac{\pi}{2}\\
									0,			\amp \text{otherwise}
								\end{array} 
							\right.
						</mrow>
					</md>
					and has the following graph
				</p>
				
				<p>
					<sidebyside width="90%" margins="0%">
						<figure xml:id="tsqrd-off-then-on-at-pi-over-2"><caption> Graph of <m>\sin (t) \cdot u_{\sfrac{\pi}{2}}(t)</m> </caption>
							<image>
								<latex-image>
									\begin{tikzpicture}[samples=200, scale=0.7]
										% === colors ===
										\def\OFColor{blue}				\def\OFFill{\OFColor!15}
										\def\ONColor{green!60!black}	\def\ONFill{\ONColor!15}

										% === figure/domain/tick bounds ===
										\def\tmin{-4}	\def\tmax{7}
										\def\ymin{-1.6}	\def\ymax{1.6}
										\def\tticks{
											{-pi}		/ $-\pi$,
											{-pi*0.5}	/ $-\frac{\pi}{2}$,
											{pi*0.5}	/ $\frac{\pi}{2}$,
											{pi}		/ $\pi$,
											{3*pi*0.5}	/ $\frac{3\pi}{2}$,
											{2*pi}		/ $2\pi$
